Act which allows all women (but not men) an automatic exemption from jury duty perpetuates a discriminatory assumption that women are not suited to public roles, or that her primary and de\ufb01 ning role relates to family responsibilities, an assumption that is not made of men. Family responsibilities and public life should be shared equally between men and women and the Juries Act 1968 needs to re\ufb02 ect this to be non-discriminatory. There are no legal barriers to women\u2019s equal right to conclude contracts and administer property. To comply with this indicator the legislation should speci\ufb01 cally nullify all contracts and instruments that limit women\u2019s legal capacity. As there is no speci\ufb01 c legislation that has this e\ufb00 ect, there is not compliance with this indicator. 82 LEGISLATIVE COMPLIANCE OF THE COOK ISLANDS 82 ARTICLE 15: EQUALITY BEFORE THE LAW AND CIVIL MATTERS ARTICLE 16: PERSONAL AND FAMILY LAW INDICATOR COMPLIANCE RELEVANT LEGISLATION COMMENTARY INDICATOR COMPLIANCE RELEVANT LEGISLATION COMMENTARY 15.7 Do women have an equal right to choose their residence and domicile? Yes There are no legal barriers to women\u2019s equal right to choose residence and domicile. 16.1 Does the legislation guarantee women\u2019s entry into marriage with full and free consent? 16.2 Does the legislation allow marriages to be nulli\ufb01 ed if they took place under force, duress or undue in\ufb02 uence? 16.3 Is there an equal minimum age of 18 for marriage? 16.4 Is there a legislative prohibition on child marriage? 16.5 Does the legislation require registration of marriage in an o\ufb03 cial registry? 16.6 Does the legislation prohibit bigamy? No No No Partial Yes Yes Marriage Act 1973, s 17(1). Minimum age for males and females is 16. Marriage Act 1973 s 17(1). A marriage licence shall not be issued by any Registrar and no marriage shall be solemnised by any Registrar or o\ufb03 ciating Minister if either of the persons intending marriage is under the 16 years but (2) No marriage shall be void by reason only of an infringement of the provisions of this section. Marriage Act 1973, s 34 (1). Crimes Act 1963, s 228. Bigamy is a criminal o\ufb00 ence - 7 years imprisonment. There is no provision that provides that marriages cannot take place under duress, force or coercion. Although the marriage age for males and females is equal the CEDAW Committ ee has recommended 18 as the minimum age for marriage for males and females. Marriages of persons under 16 cannot be solemnised, however, full compliance with the indicator requires: \u2022 Marriages of persons under 18 cannot be solemnised \u2022 That marriage is voided if either party is under 18. LEGISLATIVE COMPLIANCE OF THE COOK ISLANDS 83 ARTICLE 16: PERSONAL AND FAMILY LAW INDICATOR COMPLIANCE RELEVANT LEGISLATION COMMENTARY 16.7 Do women have an equal right to choose a family name? 16.8 Is the consent of both parents equal in the marriage of minors? 16.9 Are both spouses equal in owner- ship, acquisition, m a n a g e m e n t , a d m i n i s t r a t i o n , enjoyment and disposition of pro- perty? 16.10 Does the legislation provide for a main- tenance and custody order during separa- tion based on need? Yes Yes No Partial Marriage Act 1973 s 18. (1)(2) (a). If either of the parties to an intended marriage is a minor, consent shall be obtained from both parents. Cook Islands Act 1915, \u2022 s 422. Every title to and interest in customary land shall be determined according to the ancient custom and usage of the Natives of the Cook Islands.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ea59a23d-9eef-406f-bc3a-5e7040bcb918": {"__data__": {"id_": "ea59a23d-9eef-406f-bc3a-5e7040bcb918", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/translating-cedaw-law-cook-islands", "Author": "United